      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Distinguishing between true random error and something else interfering requires looking beyond just the p-value. Consider examining effect sizes and confidence intervals; a large effect size with a confidence interval that barely misses crossing zero suggests the true effect might be slightly stronger. Additionally, checking your data for outliers, non-normality, or model mis-specification can help identify systemic problems rather than just random noise.",
      "source": "target",
